               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CHAMBERS</hi>
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">GASELEE</hi>
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>. <hi rend="smallCaps">EDMUND HAIGHTON</hi>. I keep a draper's shop in Lambeth Marsh. On the 14th of May the prisoner came to buy a handkerchief which came to 4 ½<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he put down a bad shilling—I said, " I recollect you have been here before, and passed bad money"—he then put down a good sixpence—I got over the counter, and he ran off—a policeman who was passing pursued and took him—he dropped a shilling in going, which the officer brought to my shop—I marked the shillling which the prisoner gave me—I gave that and the other to the policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400615-name-1334" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400615-name-1334" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400615-name-1334" type="surname" value="MEEK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400615-name-1334" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MEEK</persName>
                  </hi>(<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi>48.) I ran after the prisoner and took him—I saw him put his hand in his left hand breeches pocket and take out a shilling, which fell on the ground—Chandler took it up and delivered it to me—I took it back to the shop—this is the one I received from Mr. Haighton.</p>
               <p>
